  "text": "Audit of Firefox NSS TLS/SSL Implementation - Core Protocol Files\n\nRepository: github.com/sg-evals/firefox--871325b8\n\nFILE 1: security/nss/lib/ssl/ssl3con.c\n- Primary Function: SSL 3.0/TLS Record Processing and Cipher Suite Negotiation\n- Description: This file implements the core SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0/1.1/1.2 protocol handling. It manages the handshake state machine, record-level encryption/decryption, cipher suite configuration and selection, and key derivation. The file contains critical cryptographic operations including master secret computation, connection key derivation, and server key exchange.\n- Key Data Structures: cipherSuites array (ssl3CipherSuiteCfg), kea_defs (key exchange algorithms), cipher_suite_defs (cipher suite definitions)\n- Key Functions: ssl3_ComputeMasterSecret, ssl3_DeriveConnectionKeys, ssl3_SendServerKeyExchange, ssl3_HandleServerHelloPart2, ssl3_HandleClientHelloPart2\n- Protocol Support: SSL 3.0, TLS 1.0, TLS 1.1, TLS 1.2\n\nFILE 2: security/nss/lib/ssl/tls13con.c\n- Primary Function: TLS 1.3 Handshake and Record Processing\n- Description: This file implements the TLS 1.3 protocol handling, which is significantly different from earlier TLS versions. It implements the modern handshake flow with 0-RTT support, key schedule with HKDF-based secret derivation, encrypted extensions, certificate handling, and the three-tier secret derivation system (early secrets, handshake secrets, application secrets). The file also handles session tickets and PSK resumption.\n- Key Functions: tls13_SetCipherSpec, tls13_SendServerHelloSequence, tls13_ComputeHandshakeSecrets, tls13_ComputeApplicationSecrets, tls13_DeriveSecret, tls13_SendFinished, tls13_HandleServerKeyShare, tls13_RecoverWrappedSharedSecret\n- Protocol Support: TLS 1.3\n\nFILE 3: security/nss/lib/ssl/dtlscon.c\n- Primary Function: DTLS-Specific Protocol Handling (Datagram TLS)\n- Description: This file implements DTLS (RFC 6347), a protocol variant designed for unreliable datagram transports like UDP. It handles version mapping between TLS and DTLS wire formats, retransmission timers, message fragmentation/reassembly, and out-of-order message handling. DTLS is essential for real-time applications like VoIP and WebRTC that cannot tolerate the latency of TCP.\n- Key Functions: dtls_TLSVersionToDTLSVersion, dtls_DTLSVersionToTLSVersion, dtls_RetransmitDetected, dtls_FreeHandshakeMessages, dtls_HandleHandshakeMessage, dtls_StartRetransmitTimer\n- Special Features: MTU-aware fragmentation, retransmission timers with exponential backoff, sequence number handling for unreliable delivery\n- Protocol Support: DTLS 1.0 (maps to TLS 1.1), DTLS 1.2 (maps to TLS 1.2), DTLS 1.3 (maps to TLS 1.3)\n\nFILE 4: security/nss/lib/ssl/ssl3ecc.c\n- Primary Function: ECC Cipher Suite Operations\n- Description: This file implements Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC) operations for SSL/TLS, including ECDH key exchange and ECDSA signatures. Originally part of ssl3con.c, it was extracted to isolate ECC-specific logic. The file handles conversion between named curves and EC parameters, EC public key operations, and client/server key exchange for ECDHE and ECDH cipher suites. This is critical for modern TLS connections, as ECDHE suites are preferred for forward secrecy.\n- Key Functions: ssl_NamedGroup2ECParams (converts named groups to EC parameters), ssl_ECPubKey2NamedGroup (extracts named group from EC public key), ssl3_SendECDHClientKeyExchange, ssl3_HandleECDHClientKeyExchange\n- Supported Curves: Multiple NIST and other standard elliptic curves (referenced by OID)\n- Protocol Support: SSL 3.0, TLS 1.0, 1.1, 1.2, 1.3 (through ECDHE cipher suites)\n\nFILE 5: security/nss/lib/ssl/sslexp.h\n- Primary Function: Experimental SSL API Declarations\n- Description: This header file declares experimental and unstable SSL/TLS APIs that are not guaranteed to remain available in future NSS versions. It provides low-level access to advanced features including custom TLS extension handling, anti-replay mechanisms for 0-RTT, session ticket control, and HelloRetryRequest callbacks. These APIs allow applications to customize protocol behavior beyond standard configurations.\n- Key Macros: SSL_EXPERIMENTAL_API, SSL_DEPRECATED_EXPERIMENTAL_API\n- Key Types: SSLExtensionSupport enum (defines extension support levels: none, native, native_only)\n- Key Functions: SSL_GetExtensionSupport (checks TLS extension support), SSL_InstallExtensionHooks (custom extension callbacks), SSL_CreateAntiReplayContext, SSL_SendSessionTicket, SSL_HelloRetryRequestCallback\n- Stability: These APIs are experimental and subject to change; applications must safeguard against their unavailability\n\nSUMMARY:\nAll five core files implementing TLS protocol handling in Firefox NSS have been located in the github.com/sg-evals/firefox--871325b8 repository under security/nss/lib/ssl/. These files represent the complete TLS/SSL implementation stack: legacy protocols (ssl3con.c), modern TLS 1.3 (tls13con.c), datagram transport variant (dtlscon.c), elliptic curve operations (ssl3ecc.c), and experimental APIs (sslexp.h). Together they provide comprehensive cryptographic protocol support spanning from SSL 3.0 through TLS 1.3, including both stream and datagram transports."
}

